		<item>
		<title>Obama halts immigration orders and more in today’s Briefing.</title>
		<link>http://briefi.ng/02-18-2015/561</link>
		<comments>http://briefi.ng/02-18-2015/561#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Wed, 18 Feb 2015 12:08:08 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[wvnutt]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Daily Briefing]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://briefi.ng/?p=561</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Overruled…For Now President Obama’s executive orders on immigration won’t go into effect today, nor will they anytime soon. On Tuesday, Obama announced he was putting the brakes on the actions after being blocked by a federal judge in Texas on Monday. Hundreds of thousands of undocumented immigrants, most of whom came to the U.S. as [&#8230;]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div class="row dark" id="s1">
<div class="col-xs-10 col-xs-offset-1 col-md-8 col-md-offset-2 col-lg-6 col-lg-offset-3">
<h1>Overruled…For Now</h1>
<p>President Obama’s executive orders on immigration won’t go into effect today, nor will they <a href="http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/U/US_IMMIGRATION?SITE=AP&#038;SECTION=HOME&#038;TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&#038;CTIME=2015-02-17-20-08-12" target="_blank">anytime soon</a>. On Tuesday, Obama announced he was putting the brakes on the actions after being blocked by a federal judge in Texas on Monday.</p>
<p>Hundreds of thousands of undocumented immigrants, most of whom came to the U.S. as kids, were set to apply for amnesty protections today. But they’ll have to wait, as will the undocumented parents of any children who were born legal U.S. citizens. Obama said the Department of Justice <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/18/us/obama-immigration-policy-halted-by-federal-judge-in-texas.html" target="_blank">will appeal</a> the court’s decision.</p>
<p>The court ruling is a huge win for Republicans, who have derided Obama’s immigrations actions as <a href="http://www.wsj.com/articles/judge-faults-how-quickly-obama-moved-on-immigration-changes-1424207237" target="_blank">unconstitutional</a> and an imposition on states’ rights. The ruling is also likely to embolden the GOP’s calls for withholding funding from the Department of Homeland Security (DHS) unless Obama’s immigration orders are abolished. DHS has 9 days before its current funding runs dry.</p>
<div class="line"></div>
<div class="media-logos">
                        <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/18/us/obama-immigration-policy-halted-by-federal-judge-in-texas.html" target="_blank"><img class="nyt" src="http://briefi.ng/media/nyt.svg"></a><a href="http://www.wsj.com/articles/judge-faults-how-quickly-obama-moved-on-immigration-changes-1424207237" target="_blank"><img class="wsj" src="http://briefi.ng/media/wsj.svg"></a><a href="http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/federal-judge-texas-blocks-president-obamas-executive-action/story?id=29011861" target="_blank"><img class="abc last" src="http://briefi.ng/media/abc.svg"></a>
                      </div>
<p><!-- /.media-logos -->
                    </div>
<p><!-- /col -->
               </div>
<div class="row" id="s2">
<div class="col-xs-10 col-xs-offset-1 col-md-8 col-md-offset-2 col-lg-6 col-lg-offset-3">
<h1>Too Big To Fail?</h1>
<p>Because bank failures are bad, the Treasury Department released a <a href="http://financialresearch.gov/briefs/files/2015-02-12-systemic-importance-indicators-for-us-bank-holding-companies.pdf" target="_blank">study</a> ranking banks whose (hypothetical) failure would most harm the global economy. <a href="http://www.reuters.com/article/2015/02/17/us-banks-regulations-jpmorgan-idUSKBN0LL1YL20150217" target="_blank">JPMorgan Chase Bank</a> topped the list.</p>
<p>A slew of indicators (that we wouldn’t dare try to explain) were used to measure the potential effects of a given bank’s failure. The collapse of Citigroup Bank would be the 2nd most harmful. Bank of America (3rd), Morgan Stanley (4th), and Goldman Sachs (5th) rounded out the top five.</p>
</div>
<p><!-- /col -->
               </div>
<div class="row dark" id="s3">
<div class="col-xs-10 col-xs-offset-1 col-md-8 col-md-offset-2 col-lg-6 col-lg-offset-3">
<h1>U.N. ‘N Libya?</h1>
<p>The Egyptian government clarified the kind of coalition it wants to fight Islamic terrorists in Libya. President Abdel Fattah el-Sisi said Tuesday that the coalition should be <a href="http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/M/ML_ISLAMIC_STATE?SITE=AP&#038;SECTION=HOME&#038;TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&#038;CTIME=2015-02-17-20-08-14" target="_blank">backed by the United Nations</a>.</p>
<p>Libya has been torn apart since the fall of its former dictator, Muammar Gaddafi, in 2011. Today, the country is ruled by <a href="http://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-13754897" target="_blank">rival governments</a>: an Islam-based group that controls the capital of Tripoli, and an internationally recognized, democratic group that is expected to ask the U.N. <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2015/02/17/world/middleeast/ap-un-united-nations-libya.html" target="_blank">for help</a> today. The U.N. Security Council will meet in an emergency session today to discuss the crisis.</p>
<div class="line"></div>
<div class="media-logos">
                        <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2015/02/17/world/middleeast/ap-un-united-nations-libya.html" target="_blank"><img class="nyt" src="http://briefi.ng/media/nyt.svg"></a><a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/world/middle_east/egypt-calls-for-united-nations-backed-military-operation-in-libya/2015/02/17/a70b6804-b6ad-11e4-bc30-a4e75503948a_story.html" target="_blank"><img class="wapo" src="http://briefi.ng/media/wapo.svg"></a><a href="http://www.cbsnews.com/news/egypt-el-sissi-calls-for-un-coalition-isis-libya/" target="_blank"><img class="cbsnews last" src="http://briefi.ng/media/cbsnews.svg"></a>
                      </div>
<p><!-- /.media-logos -->
                    </div>
<p><!-- /col -->
               </div>
<div class="row" id="s4">
<div class="col-xs-10 col-xs-offset-1 col-md-8 col-md-offset-2 col-lg-6 col-lg-offset-3">
<h1>What the Media Will Talk About Today</h1>
<p>Prospective Republican presidential candidate Jeb Bush will weigh in on U.S. foreign policy in a speech today in Chicago.</p>
<p><i>Reuters</i> was advanced excerpts of Bush’s <a href="http://www.reuters.com/article/2015/02/18/us-usa-politics-bush-jeb-idUSKBN0LM06F20150218" target="_blank">prepared remarks</a>, which will blister the Obama administration’s perceived weakness in the Middle East and with Russia. <a href="http://www.politico.com/story/2015/02/republican-presidential-field-2016-elections-polls-115225.html" target="_blank">Polling</a> in many key GOP primary states shows Bush at or near the top among possible 2016 presidential candidates.</p>
<div class="line"></div>
<div class="media-logos">
                        <a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/what-will-jeb-bush-have-to-say-about-foreign-policy--especially-iraq/2015/02/16/9b45b2a0-b558-11e4-aa05-1ce812b3fdd2_story.html" target="_blank"><img class="wapo" src="http://briefi.ng/media/wapo.svg"></a><a href="http://www.bloombergview.com/articles/2015-02-17/jeb-bush-wants-to-bury-the-past" target="_blank"><img class="bloomberg" src="http://briefi.ng/media/bloomberg.svg"></a><a href="http://www.wsj.com/articles/jeb-bushs-foreign-policy-seen-leaning-toward-his-fathers-1423616439" target="_blank"><img class="wsj last" src="http://briefi.ng/media/wsj.svg"></a>
                      </div>
<p><!-- /.media-logos -->
                    </div>
<p><!-- /col -->
