		<dc:creator><![CDATA[wvnutt]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Daily Briefing]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://briefi.ng/?p=487</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[All Quiet on the Eastern Front? The peace negotiations between Russia and Ukraine appear to have worked. After negotiating through the night and into the morning, Russian President Vladimir Putin and Ukrainian President Petro Poroshenko held separate press conferences announcing the tentative agreement. At the heart of the matter is the status of eastern Ukraine, [&#8230;]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div class="row dark" id="s1">
<div class="col-xs-10 col-xs-offset-1 col-md-8 col-md-offset-2 col-lg-6 col-lg-offset-3">
<h1>All Quiet on the Eastern Front?</h1>
<p>The peace negotiations between Russia and Ukraine <a href="http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/E/EU_UKRAINE?SITE=AP&#038;SECTION=HOME&#038;TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&#038;CTIME=2015-02-12-07-10-07" target="_blank">appear to have worked</a>. After negotiating through the night and into the morning, Russian President Vladimir Putin and Ukrainian President Petro Poroshenko held separate press conferences announcing the tentative agreement.</p>
<p>At the heart of the matter is the status of eastern Ukraine, where more than 5,300 people have been killed since last April. Ukraine has agreed to give the region more autonomy in exchange for Russia’s withdrawal of heavy weapons in the area; Ukraine will have control of the border. A <a href="http://www.reuters.com/article/2015/02/12/us-ukraine-crisis-idUSKBN0LG0FX20150212" target="_blank">cease-fire is scheduled</a> for Saturday at midnight.</p>
<p>The odds aren’t exactly in favor of the conflict dying down immediately. Violence has surged in eastern Ukraine in recent days, and government officials warned that much negotiating remains.</p>
<div class="line"></div>
<div class="media-logos">
                        <a href="http://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-fighting-continues-ahead-of-key-meeting-1423643630" target="_blank"><img class="wsj" src="http://briefi.ng/media/wsj.svg"></a><a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/13/world/europe/ukraine-talks-cease-fire.html?_r=0" target="_blank"><img class="nyt" src="http://briefi.ng/media/nyt.svg"></a><a href="http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/leaders-minsk-crucial-ukraine-peace-talks-28908311" target="_blank"><img class="abc last" src="http://briefi.ng/media/abc.svg"></a>
                      </div>
<p><!-- /.media-logos -->
                    </div>
<p><!-- /col -->
               </div>
<div class="row" id="s2">
<div class="col-xs-10 col-xs-offset-1 col-md-8 col-md-offset-2 col-lg-6 col-lg-offset-3">
<h1>On the Road to War … That We’re Already On</h1>
<p>Remember when <i>Rocky IV</i>’s Ivan Drago told Apollo Creed, “<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2c3Y2i-1mD0" target="_blank">You will lose</a>”? President Obama appeared to take his cue from Drago Wednesday as he called for expanded war powers against ISIS. Obama said ISIS is “<a href="http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/U/US_CONGRESS_WAR_POWERS?SITE=AP&#038;SECTION=HOME&#038;TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&#038;CTIME=2015-02-11-18-57-35" target="_blank">going to lose</a>,” but something tells us ISIS may be tougher to kill than Creed.</p>
<p><i>Bloomberg</i>’s Tuesday <a href="http://www.bloombergview.com/articles/2015-02-10/obama-s-islamic-state-war-authorization-limits-u-s-ground-forces" target="_blank">report</a> proved accurate: Obama’s Authorization for Use of Military Force (AUMF) would allow the U.S. military to pursue ISIS and related groups anywhere through 2018. The proposal would repeal the AUMF that opened the door to the Iraq War.</p>
<p>Republicans are concerned about the AUMF’s prohibition of large-scale ground troops, even though the proposal allows for combat troops in “limited circumstances.” Democrats are worried the AUMF is too open-ended, citing the protracted war in Afghanistan as Exhibit A. Ultimately, Congress is expected to approve a <a href="http://www.politico.com/story/2015/02/obama-war-authorization-congress-isil-115108.html" target="_blank">renegotiated version</a> of the measure.</p>
<div class="line"></div>
<div class="media-logos">
                        <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/12/us/obama-war-authorization-congress.html?_r=0" target="_blank"><img class="nyt" src="http://briefi.ng/media/nyt.svg"></a><a href="http://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2015/02/11/385528726/obama-war-powers-resolution-does-not-signal-new-ground-war-for-u-s" target="_blank"><img class="npr" src="http://briefi.ng/media/npr.svg"></a><a href="http://www.cnn.com/2015/02/11/politics/president-obama-isis-authorization-military-force/" target="_blank"><img class="cnn last" src="http://briefi.ng/media/cnn.svg"></a>
                      </div>
<p><!-- /.media-logos -->
                    </div>
<p><!-- /col -->
               </div>
<div class="row dark" id="s3">
<div class="col-xs-10 col-xs-offset-1 col-md-8 col-md-offset-2 col-lg-6 col-lg-offset-3">
<h1>Horror on the Hill</h1>
<p>Chapel Hill, NC remains in shock over the Tuesday murders of Deah Shaddy Barakat (23), his wife Yusor Mohammad (21) and her sister Razan Mohammad Abu-Salha (19). Craig Stephen Hicks (46), a neighbor of the three Muslim students, was charged with <a href="http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/U/US_THREE_KILLED_NORTH_CAROLINA?SITE=AP&#038;SECTION=HOME&#038;TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&#038;CTIME=2015-02-11-22-40-33" target="_blank">first-degree murder</a> in court Wednesday.</p>
<p>Hicks is an atheist, known for his frequent anti-religion Facebook postings. That detail has sparked a flurry of speculation that his alleged involvement was prompted by the Islamic faith of the victims. The families of the students and a slew of Muslim organizations called the murders a <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/12/us/muslim-student-shootings-north-carolina.html" target="_blank">hate crime</a>. The victims were found dead in their apartment with gunshot wounds to the head.</p>
<p>But local law enforcement officials are still investigating whether Hicks will be charged with a hate crime. Hicks’ wife said the incident wasn’t related to religion but to a “longstanding parking dispute.” She released a statement later Wednesday saying she’s planning to file for divorce. Hicks’ first wife and neighbors had <a href="http://www.latimes.com/nation/nationnow/la-na-north-carolina-shooting-deaths-20150211-story.html#page=1" target="_blank">less flattering things</a> to say.</p>
<div class="line"></div>
<div class="media-logos">
                        <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/12/us/muslim-student-shootings-north-carolina.html" target="_blank"><img class="nyt" src="http://briefi.ng/media/nyt.svg"></a><a href="http://abcnews.go.com/US/chapel-hill-shooting-murdered-newlyweds-clashed-neighbor-victims/story?id=28882062" target="_blank"><img class="abc" src="http://briefi.ng/media/abc.svg"></a><a href="http://www.cnn.com/2015/02/11/us/chapel-hill-shooting/" target="_blank"><img class="cnn last" src="http://briefi.ng/media/cnn.svg"></a>
                      </div>
<p><!-- /.media-logos -->
                    </div>
