<div class="row dark" id="s5">
<div class="col-xs-10 col-xs-offset-1 col-md-8 col-md-offset-2 col-lg-6 col-lg-offset-3">
<h1>Big Loss at CBS</h1>
<p>One of the country’s <a href="http://www.cbsnews.com/news/cbs-news-correspondent-bob-simon-1941-2015" target="_blank">premier journalists</a> died in a car crash Wednesday. Bob Simon’s name may not ring a bell, but you would instantly recognize him from his work on <i>60 Minutes</i>. Simon won 27 Emmys and 4 Peabody Awards for his reporting. He was 73.</p>
<p>One of <a href="http://www.cbs.com/shows/60_minutes/video/mIolz81g4QzjdaAjZe8O_k9llp_gg8m5/mandy-patinkin" target="_blank">Simon’s last interviews</a> was with Mandy Patinkin, otherwise known as “Saul Berenson” from <i>Homeland<i>.</p>
<div class="line"></div>
<div class="media-logos">
                        <a href="http://www.cbsnews.com/news/cbs-news-correspondent-bob-simon-1941-2015/" target="_blank"><img class="cbsnews" src="http://briefi.ng/media/cbsnews.svg"></a><a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/12/nyregion/bob-simon-cbs-correspondent-is-killed-in-manhattan-car-crash.html" target="_blank"><img class="nyt" src="http://briefi.ng/media/nyt.svg"></a><a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/02/11/bob-simon-veteran-60-minutes-correspondent-killed-in-car-crash/" target="_blank"><img class="wapo last" src="http://briefi.ng/media/wapo.svg"></a>
                      </div>
