		<title>The growing threat of ISIS, a Daily Show departure and more in today’s Briefing.</title>
		<link>http://briefi.ng/02-11-2015/483</link>
		<comments>http://briefi.ng/02-11-2015/483#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Wed, 11 Feb 2015 13:16:29 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[wvnutt]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Daily Briefing]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://briefi.ng/?p=483</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Murder of an Aid Worker The death of Arizona native Kayla Mueller was confirmed Tuesday. A long-time international aid worker, Mueller was captured by ISIS while leaving a hospital in Aleppo, Syria in 2013. She was 26. ISIS claims Mueller was killed during a Jordanian airstrike. U.S. officials, who confirmed Muller’s murder after her parents [&#8230;]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div class="row dark" id="s1">
<div class="col-xs-10 col-xs-offset-1 col-md-8 col-md-offset-2 col-lg-6 col-lg-offset-3">
<h1>Murder of an Aid Worker</h1>
<p>The death of Arizona native Kayla Mueller was <a href="http://www.reuters.com/article/2015/02/10/us-mideast-crisis-hostage-idUSKBN0LE1WV20150210" target="_blank">confirmed</a> Tuesday. A long-time international aid worker, Mueller was captured by ISIS while leaving a hospital in Aleppo, Syria in 2013. She was 26.</p>
<p>ISIS claims Mueller was killed during a Jordanian airstrike. U.S. officials, who confirmed Muller’s murder after her parents received related information over the weekend, said: <a href="http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/U/US_AMERICAN_ISLAMIC_STATE?SITE=AP&#038;SECTION=HOME&#038;TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&#038;CTIME=2015-02-10-15-52-49" target="_blank">B.S.</a></p>
<p>Although some thought Mueller was ISIS’s last U.S. hostage, White House spokesman Josh Earnest said Tuesday that the desert cult of death (ISIS) is holding other Americans.</p>
<div class="line"></div>
<div class="media-logos">
                        <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/11/world/middleeast/parents-of-kayla-mueller-isis-hostage-confirm-she-is-dead.html?_r=0" target="_blank"><img class="nyt" src="http://briefi.ng/media/nyt.svg"></a><a href="http://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2015/02/10/385182490/u-s-hostage-kayla-mueller-confirmed-dead" target="_blank"><img class="npr" src="http://briefi.ng/media/npr.svg"></a><a href="http://www.cnn.com/2015/02/10/world/isis-hostage-mueller/" target="_blank"><img class="cnn last" src="http://briefi.ng/media/cnn.svg"></a>
                      </div>
<p><!-- /.media-logos -->
                    </div>
<p><!-- /col -->
               </div>
<div class="row" id="s2">
<div class="col-xs-10 col-xs-offset-1 col-md-8 col-md-offset-2 col-lg-6 col-lg-offset-3">
<h1>And That Sets the Stage For…</h1>
<p>…President Obama’s request to Congress for expanded authority over the U.S.-led coalition’s fight against ISIS. That’s supposed to happen sometime today.</p>
<p><i>Bloomberg</i> <a href="http://www.bloombergview.com/articles/2015-02-10/obama-s-islamic-state-war-authorization-limits-u-s-ground-forces" target="_blank">reported</a> Tuesday that Obama’s request – known as the Authorization for Use of Military Force (AUMF) – would prevent the deployment of ground troops against ISIS through 2018. But the U.S. already has 3,000 military specialists in Iraq, and the ground force exclusion wouldn’t apply to them.</p>
<p>This stuff is really complicated, but know this: AUMFs have formed the <a href="http://www.radiolab.org/story/60-words" target="_blank">backbone of U.S. military policy</a> in the Middle East since 9/11. President Bush passed AUMFs in 2001 and 2002. The first authorized the use of force against al-Qaeda terrorist groups anywhere, anytime; the second allowed Bush to proceed with the Iraq War.</p>
<p>Obama’s request would reportedly keep Bush’s first AUMF intact (to hunt down ISIS and other groups wherever they lurk), but would abolish the second.</p>
<div class="line"></div>
<div class="media-logos">
                        <a href="http://www.npr.org/blogs/itsallpolitics/2015/02/10/385170378/in-white-house-memory-a-u-m-f-translates-to-b-u-s-h" target="_blank"><img class="npr" src="http://briefi.ng/media/npr.svg"></a><a href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/02/10/obama-war-authorization-islamic-state_n_6634136.html" target="_blank"><img class="huffpo" src="http://briefi.ng/media/huffpo.svg"></a><a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/obama-to-seek-congressional-authorization-to-fight-islamic-state/2015/02/10/c150d2d2-b160-11e4-854b-a38d13486ba1_story.html" target="_blank"><img class="wapo last" src="http://briefi.ng/media/wapo.svg"></a>
                      </div>
<p><!-- /.media-logos -->
                    </div>
<p><!-- /col -->
               </div>
<div class="row dark" id="s3">
<div class="col-xs-10 col-xs-offset-1 col-md-8 col-md-offset-2 col-lg-6 col-lg-offset-3">
<h1>Warrantlessly Wired</h1>
<p>A group of AT&#038;T customers couldn’t produce <a href="http://www.reuters.com/article/2015/02/10/us-usa-security-ruling-idUSKBN0LE2U820150210" target="_blank">enough evidence</a> to warrant a valid lawsuit against the National Security Agency, a federal judge ruled Tuesday.</p>
<p>The plaintiffs sued the NSA for allegedly intercepting emails without a warrant, which would violate the <a href="http://www.law.cornell.edu/constitution/fourth_amendment" target="_blank">4th Amendment</a> of the Constitution (which says, in so many words, “You gotta have a damn good reason to spy on someone.”)</p>
<p>Their case was made more difficult in that the gathering of said “evidence” could’ve involved the unearthing of state secrets. Plaintiffs aren’t allowed to sue over government hush-hush material.</p>
<div class="line"></div>
<div class="media-logos">
                        <a href="http://www.wsj.com/articles/judge-denies-portion-of-privacy-groups-lawsuit-against-nsa-1423617737" target="_blank"><img class="wsj" src="http://briefi.ng/media/wsj.svg"></a><a href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/02/10/nsa-warrantless-searches_n_6656314.html" target="_blank"><img class="huffpo" src="http://briefi.ng/media/huffpo.svg"></a><a href="http://dfw.cbslocal.com/2015/02/11/judge-sides-with-nsa-in-surveillance-lawsuit/" target="_blank"><img class="cbsnews last" src="http://briefi.ng/media/cbsnews.svg"></a>
                      </div>
<p><!-- /.media-logos -->
                    </div>
<p><!-- /col -->
               </div>
<div class="row" id="s4">
<div class="col-xs-10 col-xs-offset-1 col-md-8 col-md-offset-2 col-lg-6 col-lg-offset-3">
<h1>Unfunny News   </h1>
<p>Comedian Jon Stewart <a href="http://www.mediaite.com/tv/jon-stewart-on-leaving-daily-show-it-is-time-for-someone-else" target="_blank">announced</a> last night that he’ll leave <i>The Daily Show</i> later this year. The exact date of departure hasn’t been determined.</p>
<p>Stewart has been the host of every-college-student’s-favorite-political-show since 1999, and along the way, he proved a comedian could be<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aFQFB5YpDZE" target="_blank"> just as important</a> to journalism as, say, Walter Cronkite.</p>
<p>The news isn’t a total surprise. Stewart took the summer off to direct his first feature film and was approached to <a href="http://www.rollingstone.com/tv/news/jon-stewart-on-meet-the-press-offer-they-were-casting-a-wide-and-weird-net-20141030" target="_blank">take over</a> for David Gregory on <i>Meet the Press</i> last fall.</p>
<div class="line"></div>
<div class="media-logos">
                        <a href="http://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2015/02/11/385405483/watch-jon-stewart-break-the-news-of-his-departure-to-an-audience" target="_blank"><img class="npr" src="http://briefi.ng/media/npr.svg"></a><a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/11/arts/television/jon-stewart-leaving-daily-show.html" target="_blank"><img class="nyt" src="http://briefi.ng/media/nyt.svg"></a><a href="http://time.com/3704321/jon-stewart-daily-show-fake-news/" target="_blank"><img class="time last" src="http://briefi.ng/media/time.svg"></a>
                      </div>
<p><!-- /.media-logos -->
                    </div>
<p><!-- /col -->
               </div>
<div class="row dark" id="s5">
<div class="col-xs-10 col-xs-offset-1 col-md-8 col-md-offset-2 col-lg-6 col-lg-offset-3">
<h1>Peace Talks Falling Apart?  </h1>
<p>Today’s scheduled peace talks between Russia and Ukraine in Minsk, Belarus were made a lot tougher Tuesday. 19 Ukrainian military personnel were killed in an <a href="http://www.reuters.com/article/2015/02/11/us-ukraine-crisis-idUSKBN0LF0ZM20150211" target="_blank">attack by Russian separatists</a>, accounting for some of the worst violence since the conflict started last April.</p>
<p>Germany and France spearheaded today’s meeting between Russian President Vladimir Putin and Ukrainian President Petro Poroshenko. Many European leaders believe Tuesday’s violence will make any chance of an immediate truce all but impossible.</p>
<div class="line"></div>
<div class="media-logos">
                        <a href="http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2015/02/11/ukraine-europe-leaders-peace-deal/23220411/" target="_blank"><img class="usatoday" src="http://briefi.ng/media/usatoday.svg"></a><a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/12/world/europe/meeting-of-world-leaders-in-belarus-aims-to-address-ukraine-conflict.html" target="_blank"><img class="nyt" src="http://briefi.ng/media/nyt.svg"></a><a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/annaborshchevskaya/2015/02/10/ahead-of-minsk-talks-west-needs-a-comprehensive-solution-on-ukraine/" target="_blank"><img class="forbes last" src="http://briefi.ng/media/forbes.svg"></a>
                      </div>
