		<title>RadioShack files for bankruptcy, the January jobs report and more in today’s Briefing.</title>
		<link>http://briefi.ng/02-06-2015/461</link>
		<comments>http://briefi.ng/02-06-2015/461#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Fri, 06 Feb 2015 13:07:30 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[wvnutt]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Daily Briefing]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://briefi.ng/?p=461</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[The Labor Department releases its January jobs report this morning. Analysts expect the report to show about 230,000 jobs created last month, which would mark the 12th consecutive month above 200,000. The unemployment rate—currently 5.6%—is expected to remain unchanged. The Obama administration today releases its second—and final—national security strategy. Required by Congress, the document outlines [&#8230;]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div class="row dark" id="s1">
<div class="col-xs-10 col-xs-offset-1 col-md-8 col-md-offset-2 col-lg-6 col-lg-offset-3">
<h1>The Labor Department releases its January jobs report this morning.</h1>
<p>Analysts expect the report to show about 230,000 jobs created last month, which would mark the 12th consecutive month above 200,000. The unemployment rate—currently 5.6%—is expected to remain unchanged.</p>
<div class="line"></div>
<div class="media-logos">
                        <a href="http://www.usatoday.com/story/money/markets/2015/02/05/what-to-watch-employment-report-january/22955949/" target="_blank"><img class="usatoday" src="http://briefi.ng/media/usatoday.svg"></a><a href="http://blogs.wsj.com/briefly/2015/02/05/5-things-to-watch-in-the-january-jobs-report/" target="_blank"><img class="wsj" src="http://briefi.ng/media/wsj.svg"></a><a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/another-month-of-solid-job-growth-is-expected-for-january/2015/02/06/de204cb8-add6-11e4-8876-460b1144cbc1_story.html" target="_blank"><img class="wapo last" src="http://briefi.ng/media/wapo.svg"></a>
                      </div>
<p><!-- /.media-logos -->
                    </div>
<p><!-- /col -->
               </div>
<div class="row" id="s2">
<div class="col-xs-10 col-xs-offset-1 col-md-8 col-md-offset-2 col-lg-6 col-lg-offset-3">
<h1>The Obama administration today releases its second—and final—national security strategy.</h1>
<p>Required by Congress, the document outlines the president’s foreign policy priorities, detailing his plan for American leadership while acknowledging limits to how much the U.S. can influence world events. Obama includes a diverse list of eight strategic risks, including a homeland attack, disruptions in the energy market and climate change. He also addresses the threat of cyberterrorism and makes priorities of eliminating global poverty within 15 years and promoting the rights of LGBT people around the world—a first for a national security strategy.</p>
<p>As many experts have criticized Obama&#8217;s reluctance to assert American power, the document defends his handling of crises in the Middle East and Ukraine.</p>
<div class="line"></div>
<div class="media-logos">
                        <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/06/us/politics/security-strategy-recognizes-us-limits.html" target="_blank"><img class="nyt" src="http://briefi.ng/media/nyt.svg"></a><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/obamas-national-security-strategy-version-2-0-051004198.html;_ylt=AwrBJR6htNRU4SIAfY_QtDMD" target="_blank"><img class="yahoo" src="http://briefi.ng/media/yahoo.svg"></a><a href="http://www.usatoday.com/story/theoval/2015/02/05/obama-susan-rice-national-security-strategy/22931715/" target="_blank"><img class="usatoday last" src="http://briefi.ng/media/usatoday.svg"></a>
                      </div>
<p><!-- /.media-logos -->
                    </div>
<p><!-- /col -->
               </div>
<div class="row dark" id="s3">
<div class="col-xs-10 col-xs-offset-1 col-md-8 col-md-offset-2 col-lg-6 col-lg-offset-3">
<h1>RadioShack filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy yesterday.</h1>
<p>Amid a series of failed efforts to reinvent itself in the digital age, the 94-year-old electronics chain has been losing money since 2011.</p>
<p>Under the agreement, 4,000 stores will be closed and up to 2,400 others sold to hedge fund Standard General, RadioShack’s largest shareholder. Sprint will open mini-shops in as many as 1,750 of the acquired stores, which will primarily feature the wireless carrier’s branding on storefronts and in marketing materials.</p>
<div class="line"></div>
<div class="media-logos">
                        <a href="http://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2015/02/05/384128304/radioshack-the-electronics-chain-files-for-bankruptcy" target="_blank"><img class="npr" src="http://briefi.ng/media/npr.svg"></a><a href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/02/05/radioshack-bankruptcy_n_6625482.html" target="_blank"><img class="huffpo" src="http://briefi.ng/media/huffpo.svg"></a><a href="http://www.cbsnews.com/news/5-mistakes-that-doomed-radioshack/" target="_blank"><img class="cbsnews last" src="http://briefi.ng/media/cbsnews.svg"></a>
                      </div>
<p><!-- /.media-logos -->
                    </div>
<p><!-- /col -->
               </div>
